## 1.4 PII & Data Privacy Regulations
Personally Identifiable Information (PII): This is any data that can be used to distinguish or trace an individual's identity (e.g., name, BVN, NIN, email, or biometric records).

The Power of Combination: You correctly noted that strings of data, which might seem harmless alone, can identify someone when combined (this is often called the "Mosaic Effect").

GDPR (General Data Protection Regulation): This is the "Gold Standard" of privacy laws in the EU, granting individuals the Right to be Forgotten and the Right to Access their data.

Enforcement & Sanctions: Violators (including data brokers and financial institutions) face massive fines—up to €20 million or 4% of global annual turnover, whichever is higher.

## 1.4 HIPAA & Healthcare Data Security
Core Mandate: HIPAA ensures that all Protected Health Information (PHI) is handled with strict adherence to the CIA Triad.

Target Entities: It applies to "Covered Entities," which includes health institutions, insurance providers, and any third-party data handlers.

Industry Standards: It sets the benchmark for how health data must be encrypted (Confidentiality), protected from unauthorized changes (Integrity), and remain accessible to medical staff during emergencies (Availability).
 
